title: A bunch of fixes to express declaration
body:
Disclaimer: I'm new to TypeScript, Node.js and express.js. I wanted to be able to import express and have it usable in a way that is close to the JavaScript usage. At first I had troubles getting importing to work, the Response class did not support calling end etc. I started reading the specification and found some threads about how to write declaration files and this is what I came up with. Sorry for putting it all in one commit, would have been too annoying to split it up after I moved most interfaces into the e module.

The end result is that you can import express, call it as a function and access members from it. Additionally it doesn't pollute the global namespace with members that have Express as a prefix.

title: Fixed the definitions for local and sync storage.
body:
reference: [Chrome StorageArea Documentation](http://developer.chrome.com/extensions/storage.html#type-StorageArea)
`Local` and `Sync` are both types of `StorageArea`. You could think of `StorageArea` as an abstract class of sorts - they use it as reference in their docs, but really you're supposed to replace `StorageArea` with `local` or `sync`. I reflected this in the definition file by having `Local` and `Sync` extend `StorageArea`.

debounce (target, method, args*, wait, immediate): void

arguments in the middle means we can only ever type everything after
method as "...any".
